Reading an old memoire of a Bulgarian writer and he recalls talking with his mother as a child, circa 1900s, and after someone mentioned Sappho, she got angry and exclaimed "why do we need that new Sappho, we have good enough Bulgarian poets", naming a few from the 19th century

Very curious interplay between "time", "space", "era", where something from 2700 years ago, but foreign, is perceived as a novelty, while far more recent, but local texts are seen as "foundational" and take precedence over any ancient Greek culture. "Hermeneutics", I guess.

But basically if like French intellectuals suddenly get obsessed with antediluvian Papuan poetry and start trying to expand it into other countries' literature, one would be correct to see it as a "trend", how a thing is deployed matters more than its historical age, new and old.
